| Method Overloading in Java |
==============================
👉 Method Overloading is the process of creating multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists in the same class.
   👉 Same method name.
   👉 Same class.
   👉 Different parameter list.
   👉 Parameters can differ by:
   👉 Number of parameters
   👉 Type of parameters
   👉 Order of parameter types
   👉 Return type alone cannot overload a method.
   👉 Resolved at compile time.

methodName(type1 parameter1)
methodName(type1 parameter1, type2 parameter2)
methodName(type1 parameter1, type2 parameter2, type3 parameter3)
------------------------------------------------------------------------ // Different Number of Parameters
public class Main {
    public static void show() {
        System.out.println("No Parameter");
    }

    public static void show(String name) {
        System.out.println("Name : " + name);
    }

    public static void show(String name, int age) {
        System.out.println(name + " " + age);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        show();
        show("Mridul");
        show("Rahul", 18);
    }
}

👉 Method Signature -> A method signature consists of the method name and its parameter list. It does not include the return type.
                        add(int,int)
👉 Compile-Time Polymorphism -> Compile-Time Polymorphism is the ability of Java to decide which overloaded method to call during compilation.

=========================
| Pass by Value in Java |
=========================
👉 Pass by Value means that a copy of the actual value is passed to the method. 
   Changes made to the copied value do not affect the original variable.
   👉 Java is always Pass by Value.
   👉 A copy of the value is passed.
   👉 Original variable remains unchanged (for primitives).
   👉 For objects, the reference is copied, not the object itself.
   👉 Java does not support Pass by Reference.

public class Main {
    public static void change(int num) {
        num = 50;
        System.out.println("Inside Method : " + num);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 10;
        change(x);
        System.out.println("Outside Method : " + x);

    }
}

O/P : Inside Method : 50
      Outside Method : 10

==========================
| Variable Scope in Java |
==========================
👉 Variable Scope is the region of a program where a variable is accessible.
   👉 Scope defines where a variable can be used.
   👉 Variables are only accessible within their scope.
   👉 A variable cannot be accessed outside its scope.
   👉 Java has different types of variable scopes.

👉 Local Variable -> A local variable is declared inside a method, constructor, or block and can only be accessed within that method or block.
   public class Main {
       public static void show() {
           int age = 18;               // Local Variable
           System.out.println(age);
       }
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           show();
       }
   }

   Method Starts
         │
         ▼
   Variable Created
         │
         ▼
   Method Executes
         │
         ▼
   Method Ends
         │
         ▼
   Variable Destroyed

👉 Instance Variable -> An instance variable is declared inside a class but outside all methods, constructors, and blocks. 
                        Each object has its own copy of instance variables.

   class Student {
       String name;    // Instance Variable
   }
   
   public class Main {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           Student s1 = new Student();
           Student s2 = new Student();
           s1.name = "Mridul";
           s2.name = "Rahul";
           System.out.println(s1.name);
           System.out.println(s2.name);
       }
   }

👉 Static Variable -> A static variable belongs to the class rather than to any object. Only one copy of a static variable exists, 
                      and it is shared by all objects.

   class Student {
       static String school = "ABC School";  // Static Variable
   }
   
   public class Main {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           Student s1 = new Student();
           Student s2 = new Student();
           System.out.println(s1.school);
           System.out.println(s2.school);
       }
   }

👉 Block Scope -> A variable declared inside a block ({}) can only be accessed within that block.
   
   public class Main {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              if (true) {
                  int x = 100;                 // Block Scope
                  System.out.println(x);
              }
          }
      }

👉 Variable Shadowing -> Variable Shadowing occurs when a local variable has the same name as an instance or class variable, 
                      hiding the outer variable within its scope.

   class Student {
       String name = "Mridul";
       public void show() {
           String name = "Rahul";
           System.out.println(name);
           System.out.println(this.name);
       }
   }

-----------------
| Scope Summary |
-----------------
_________________________________________________________________________________________________________
| Variable Type | Declared Where             | Scope        | Lifetime                                  |
| ------------- | -------------------------- | ------------ | ----------------------------------------- |
| Local         | Inside method              | Method only  | Until method ends                         |
| Instance      | Inside class               | Object       | Until object is destroyed                 |
| Static        | Inside class with `static` | Entire class | Until program ends (or class is unloaded) |
| Block         | Inside `{}`                | Block only   | Until block ends                          |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

